measures.name: mech_adjust_thermostat_setpoints_by_degrees_copy
measures.display_name: Adjust Thermostat Setpoints by Degrees Copy
measures.description: This measure adjusts heating and cooling setpoints by a user specified number of degrees. This is applied throughout the entire building.
measures.modeler_description: This measure will clone all of the schedules that are used as heating and cooling setpoints for thermal zones. The clones are hooked up to the thermostat in place of the original schedules. Then the schedules are adjusted by the specified values. There is a checkbox to determine if the thermostat for design days should be altered.

measures.name: openstudio_results
measures.description: This measure creates high level tables and charts pulling both from model inputs and EnergyPlus results. It has building level information as well as detail on space types, thermal zones, HVAC systems, envelope characteristics, and economics. Click the heading above a chart to view a table of the chart data.
measures.modeler_description: For the most part consumption data comes from the tabular EnergyPlus results, however there are a few requests added for time series results. Space type and loop details come from the OpenStudio model. The code for this is modular, making it easy to use as a template for your own custom reports. The structure of the report uses bootstrap, and the graphs use dimple js. The new measure warning section will show warnings generated by upstream measures. It will not show forward translation warnings, EnergyPlus warnings, or warnings that might be reported by this measure.

arguments.option_1: Option 1 Description: This measure creates high level tables and charts pulling both from model inputs and EnergyPlus results. measures.name: time_series_objective_function_copy
measures.description: Creates Objective Function from Timeseries Data
measures.modeler_description: Creates Objective Function from Timeseries Data.  The measure applies a Norm at each timestep between the difference of CSV metered data and SQL model data. A timeseries plot can also be created.  Possible outputs are 'cvrmse', 'nmbe', 'simdata' = sum of the simulated data, 'csvdata' = sum of metered data, 'diff' = P Norm between the metered and simulated data if Norm is 1 or 2, else its just the Difference.
